Why “Loud” Doesn’t Matter in OT Networks
A Practitioner’s Look at Network Visibility in Municipal Water and Wastewater Operations
Joshua Brunner | github.com/Papaperun/OT-Quest | linkedin.com/in/joshua-brunner-098195270
Introduction
This paper is written for operations professionals — the people who run the systems, not the people who design security frameworks. If you have spent time in a control room, at a panel board, or watching trends on a historian screen, this is written for you. The goal is not to alarm you. The goal is to show you something that is already happening, explain why it matters, and give you a simple way to see it for yourself.
In April 2026, I built a Modbus server simulation in my home lab and scanned it with a free network tool called Nmap. It took one command and six seconds to find it. Nothing alerted. This paper explains what that means for the facilities we operate every day.
What Is Nmap?
Nmap is a free, open-source network scanning tool that has been available to the public since 1997. Think of it like a knock on every door in a neighborhood. You run one command, point it at a network, and it tells you what devices are online, what ports are open, and in many cases what kind of device or service is running behind that port.
It is widely used by IT security professionals, network administrators, and unfortunately, attackers. It requires no special skill to run. It is free to download. It runs on any laptop.
What Is Modbus?
Modbus is a communication protocol that has been used in industrial control systems since 1979. If you have a PLC talking to an HMI, or a chemical dosing pump reporting status back to a control system, there is a good chance Modbus is the language they are speaking. It is reliable, simple, and everywhere in water and wastewater operations.
It was designed in an era when these systems were completely isolated. There was no internet. There was no remote access. Security was not part of the design because connection to the outside world was not part of the design. That world no longer exists, but the protocol is still running.
One of the most important things to understand about Modbus is that it does not verify who is talking to it. It will respond to any device that sends it a valid request. There is no handshake, no authentication, no check to confirm the request is coming from a trusted source. It was not built for that. It was built to be simple and fast.
The Demonstration
I set up a Modbus TCP server simulation on my home network using Python and a library called pyModbus. I then ran the following Nmap command from a separate machine on the same network:
nmap -p 5020 192.168.x.x/24
This command scanned every device on the local network for port 5020, the port my simulation was running on. Port 5020 was used for the simulation to avoid conflicts on my home network — in a real environment, an attacker would scan port 502, the standard Modbus port. The result came back in six seconds on my small home network. A larger facility network would take longer — but an attacker is not in a hurry, and there is nothing watching the clock.
