Each line above is Nmap knocking on a door. RST ACK means the port is closed — the host replied with nothing here. Every probe is visible on the wire. All of it logged in real time. None of it alerted anyone.
To confirm what the scan looked like on the wire, I also ran Wireshark simultaneously. Wireshark is a free tool that lets you watch network traffic in real time. Think of it like standing next to a pipe and being able to see everything flowing through it. The Wireshark capture showed every probe packet Nmap sent — every knock on every door — visible and logged in real time.
Here is what the three views looked like:
Attacker view: Full network inventory returned in 6 seconds. Modbus server identified with port status open.
Network view: Wireshark captured every probe packet in real time. Every scan request visible on the wire.
Defender view: Nothing. No alert. No log. No notification. Silence.

The Wireshark capture was only visible because I was already sitting there watching. Nobody in a typical municipal OT environment has Wireshark running. Nobody is watching that traffic. The scan happened, the server was found, and the historian just kept logging tank levels like nothing occurred.
The Detection Gap
In IT environments — banking, corporate networks, larger government systems — a scan like this would likely generate an alert. There are systems called SIEMs that aggregate logs from across the network and flag unusual activity. There are security operations centers with analysts watching those alerts. A port scan generates logs. Those logs go somewhere. Someone sees them.
In most municipal OT environments, none of that infrastructure exists. This is not negligence. It is the result of a technology gap that moved faster than operations could follow. Most of the tools and protocols running in our facilities were designed and installed before cybersecurity was a consideration for this industry. The historian that shows you a pump turned on or a pressure changed was not built to tell you someone was knocking on the door before that happened. From an operator's perspective, nothing changes on the screen. Pumps run, levels trend, alarms behave normally. The scan is invisible because there is nothing designed to make it visible.
That gap is the point. Not the tool. The tool is just a knock. The problem is that nobody built a doorbell.
This is also why the term “loud” loses its meaning in OT. In IT security, we say Nmap is loud because detection systems will see it. In an OT environment with no detection layer, there is no loud or quiet. There is only seen and unseen. Right now, almost everything is unseen.
It is worth noting that Nmap offers scan types often described as “stealth” — the most common being the SYN scan (-sS). The idea is that by never completing a full TCP handshake, the scan avoids showing up in application-layer logs. That part is technically true. But stealth only means something if something is listening at the network layer. A SYN scan still generates packets on the wire. Wireshark sees every one of them. Any network monitoring tool would too. The scan is only quiet relative to tools that are already there. In most municipal OT environments those tools are not there. Whether an attacker runs the loudest scan or the quietest one, the result is the same — nobody sees it.
What You Can Do About It
⚠  IMPORTANT — READ BEFORE YOU DO ANYTHING
Do not run Nmap or any network scanning tool on any system you do not own or have explicit written authorization to scan. This is not a suggestion. Unauthorized scanning of industrial control systems and OT networks can cause real operational disruption — devices can lock up, communications can drop, processes can behave unexpectedly. In a water or wastewater facility, that has consequences beyond a crashed computer.
The demonstration in this paper was performed on an isolated home lab simulation that I built, own, and am solely responsible for. If you want to try this yourself, do it on your own isolated lab environment, or obtain written authorization from your operations leadership and document it before you run a single command. Own the outcome before you run the scan.
The same tool that an attacker can use to find your assets is a tool you can use to know what you have. Asset inventory is one of the hardest problems in small municipal OT. Most facilities do not have a complete, current picture of every device on their network. Nmap can help build that picture — but only when used correctly and with full authorization.
Running a periodic authorized scan of your own OT network gives you a baseline. Once you know what normal looks like, anything new stands out. A device that was not there last week and is there today is worth a question. That question might have a good answer. Or it might not.
This process can be scripted to run automatically. It does not require expensive software. It does not require a security operations center. It requires a scheduled scan, a saved baseline, and someone who looks at the difference.
It can also run on low-cost hardware no bigger than a credit card. A Raspberry Pi Zero W2 can run Nmap on a scheduled basis and report results. The software is free. The visibility it provides costs nothing but the time to set it up.
Closing Thought
This is not written to say our facilities are under active attack. It is written to say that if they were, we would probably not know. The same scan that took six seconds in my home lab might take an attacker considerably longer on a larger facility network. But that is not the point. The point is that nobody is looking for it. The scan runs. The results come back. And the historian just keeps logging tank levels like nothing happened.
Nothing.
The tool is not the threat.
The missing visibility is.
